title: For Sale:  PKM Semi Automatic belt fed 7.62x54r
postcontent:
I am looking to sell or trade my New(unfired) PKM 

Here is a small history on the weapon

-Automatic 7.62X54R

Kalashnikov designed General Purpose Machine Gun.

PKM Beltfed Semi-Automatic 7.62X54R with COLLECTOR KIT. 

Probably Collectible?  There is no doubt that this will become a very collectable weapon for a variety of reasons.  For one thing the ammunition is so inexpensive for this weapon that it offsets the cost greatly.  Why do PKM's cost so much you may ask, it's because there are very few in the USA that were ever imported.  The PKM is often touted as the best machine gun in the world for it's class.  It is lightweight, accurate and unbelievably dependable.  Most the countries in the world have adopted it with exception of the US military, who unofficially uses the weapon in battle also.  

I accept Postal Money Order, Cashiers Check, Certified Check, or Personal Check after clearing.

Sheepdog Concept is a private collector and not a licensed firearms dealer.  The sale and trading of items reflect the changing focus of the collection.  

Condition: Like new perfect condition.  A rare collectable and functioning modern day masterpiece!

More Information

The PKM is a Kalashnikov-designed and manufactured GPMG (General Purpose Machine Gun) that is in use all over the world, most visibly recently in the middle East. Copies of the PKM are produced in other countries (mostly Eastern-bloc). Its reliability, simplicity, and relative light weight (20 lbs with bipod) has made it very especially popular in 2nd and 3rd-world nations, and has seen use by PSCs (Private Security Contractors) in Iraq. Vltor (Wiselite Arms)  manufactures PKM receivers for building up complete weapons from parts kits to qualified organizations, and also complete weapons. Vltor (Wiselite Arms)  made improvements to the original PKM receiver design including strengthening in problem areas and machined receiver rails instead of stamped.

The PKM fires the 7.62x54mmR (rimmed) cartridge, one of the oldest military cartridges in the world. The famous Russian sniper rifle, the Dragunov SVD, uses this same round. Contrary to most belt fed weapons, the PKM feeds a metal belt from the right side of the receiver. If the barrel and gas piston tube of the PK look like an upside-down AK, that's because it's basically an AK-action turned upside down. The feel of the PKM is familiar to those who've handled Soviet-designed weapons. The pistol grip and stock are characteristic to that genre, as is the stamped metal construction. 

The PKMs we fired are in the light machine gun role, with a simple gas-tube mounted sheet metal bipod. The bipod is held under the barrel by a clip and when released, springs open. Loading the PKM is done by pressing the catch at the rear of the top cover, which should be familiar to AK shooters when they remove the top cover. The top cover is lifted open and a belt is laid in the feedway against the stop. The cover is snapped shut and the cocking handle on the right is pulled back, which makes the weapon ready to fire. 

One cool feature of the PKM is that the ejection port dust cover on the left side of the receiver is spring loaded and stays closed and only opens as an empty cases is ejected. The link ejection port above it also has a spring loaded dust cover that is opened when the bolt is pulled to the rear.

Shooting impression - it's light for that size caliber, accurate, and just very pleasant to shoot.

Improvements


Compared to conventional PKM receivers, Vltor's (Wiselite Arms)  receiver is more robust, rigid and wear resistant. Vltor (Wiselite Arms)  has researched the PKMs history and found the weaknesses of the existing chassis and moved forward to improve upon its design. For example, the PKM receiver was notorious for cracking around the rear trunnion rivet holes. This was cured through increased strengthening around the said holes. Another downside to the original PKM receiver was the excessive wear on the receiver's rails. 

Vltor (Wiselite Arms) has remedied the problem by the eliminating the conventional "stamped" rails by replacing them with fully machined, heat-treated tool steel rails. Finally, with the installation of the tool steel rails, the Vltor (Wiselite Arms) PKM receiver is less likely to flex or twist during operation, when compared to the original.

title: For Sale:  Yugo Kar98 RAD 145 Mod98/48, INTACT IRON EAGLE
postcontent:
Interesting example of a Yugoslavian captured Kar98. The rifle is an excellent shooter, barrel is shiny and new looking. Firearm has no trouble or failures of any sort. I had it appraised recently at Cabellas for 700.

The rifle is a fine example of a Yugo capture, all part numbers are matching (including stock, bolt, magazine plate, barrel), shoots extremely well, stamped Mod98/48 (means it was one of the few redone after 1950). These rifles were made with newer production Yugo barrel and are excellent shooters. Stamped RAD 145, meaning it came from workshop 145, which is an unusual specimen seeing as no one knows the location or anything about this workshop. Most Yugos came from PREDUZECE 44, while this one did not. Also quite unusual (and quite exciting) is the presence of an iron eagle and swastika hidden behind the bolt handle as well as a couple Waffenamps. When these rifles were refinished by the arsenals all German markings were scrubbed off, but in this rare case they missed one (as well as a couple other Waffenamps stamps on the barrel bands). It is visible only when the bolt is removed, which could be explained how the scrubbers missed this one.

Not interested in Trades, but feel free to make a suggestion if you like.

Also I have nearly 500 rounds of various ammo, mostly Romanian steel core on stripper clips. I also have reloading supplies including die set, powder, bullets and primers. Feel free to inquire as I'd rather move all this in one batch but it's certainly not required.
Thank you for looking.
